<br>
I've done a dual boot of linux/windows for so long now ...<br>
<br>
This is how *I* would do it.  <br>
<br>
Blast away your partitions and just install one FAT32 for the moment.<br>
<br>
First install Linux.  Linux should give you the option of repartitioning.  Just repartition the part that you need with the linux partition and swap space.  Install it so that it's boot sector is beneath 1024 cylinder head.  Linux's boot sector really does *NOT* like to be above that.  While installing linux, create a lilo boot disk.  This will be very important very soon.  After you have gotten linux installed, be sure you can boot into it without any problems.<br>
<br>
After you have verified the install of linux, go ahead and reinstall XP.  This is where you can change the remaining part of the partition to an NTFS.  After you install XP, it should over write the MBR, and you won't be able to boot into your linux partition.  Microsoft sucks ass like this.  <br>
<br>
Even *IF* it does recognize linux ... I would *NOT* let it boot up linux, use lilo for that.  Lilo can boot both operating systems just fine, where windows typically cannot.  So, what you need to do here is grab the lilo disk you made and toss it in the drive and reboot the computer.  This will enable you to boot back into linux.  <br>
<br>
Once you get booted up, log in as root.  We'll need to reconfigure lilo so that it can boot windows as well.  The lilo config file can be found at /etc/lilo.conf.  Though, there should be a nice utility called liloconfig.  This, on slackware, is found at /sbin/liloconfig.  I do believe it will give you options for booting up another operating system and will automatically config your /etc/lilo.config for you.<br>
<br>
After you have ran through that little tool, just type lilo at a command prompt to ensure that it writes to the MBR just fine, and next time you boot, you should have the option to boot into windows or linux.<br>
